<h1>@HI{{sonkeigo}}: Honorific Language</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

@include{{"honorific-humble-verbs-table.inc"}}

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{sonkeigo}} is used when referring to the other party's actions or state and serves show respect to that party.
</p>

<p>
Verbs are affected in various ways.
</p>

<h3> Passive verbs as @HI{{sonkeigo}} </h3>

<p>
<a href="grammar-verb-formation-passive.html">Passive</a> verbs are considered to be respectful. 

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{in^village}}sanha7@KJ{{time}}ni@KJ{{come}}raremasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Nakamura is coming at seven.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3> @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{ninaru}} </h3>

<p>
The @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{ninaru}} construction can be used for most verbs to produce a
respectful form of most verbs. This form is considered
to be more respectful than using the passive.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{company^long}}hamouo@KJ{{homecoming}}rininarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The company president has already left for home.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3> Special Respectful Verb Forms </h3>

<p>
The @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{ninaru}} construction cannot be used with some verbs.
These verbs have special respectful forms, as shown
in the table above. These are considered to have the same level of respectfulness as  the
@HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{ninaru}}
construction.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{douzo@KJ{{seduce}}shi@KJ{{above}}gattekudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please help yourselves.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3> @HI{{o}}@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{kudasai}} </h3>

<p>
This is the respectful way of instructing or inviting someone to do something.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{achirakarao}}@KJ{{enter}}@HI{{rikudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please enter from over there.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3> Nouns, Adjectives and Adverbs </h3>

<p>
Nouns, adjectives and adverbs also have a respectful form. This is formed by prefixing with @HI{{o}} or @HI{{go}}.
</p>

<h3> @HI{{mashite}} </h3>

<p>
To be very polite, change @Vte{{}} to @Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashite}}.
</p>

